Introduction & Motivation

We are interested in how we can attempt to predict the profitability of farming by different farming practices. Specifically we are curious about sustainable agriculture decisions and decisions about crop types. From a conservationist perspective, it is important that sustainable choices are economically viable for farmers.

https://www.nass.usda.gov/AgCensus/

Our data is sourced from the United States Census of Agriculture, between the years 2009 and 2017, along with county demographic information from Wikipedia, sourced from the U.S Census.

Our response variable in reported farm income, and we are planning to predict it with a number of variables (pop_density, farm acres, bee colonies, grazing rotation, fertilizer use)

Dataset & Wrangling

The final model suggested by best subsets regression is the 4-predictor model with pop_dens_2, grazing_rotation_2, fertilizer_use_2, and bee_colonies_2 WITHOUT farm_acres_2. This model had the lowest BIC score of -1914.5 and the lowest \(C_p\) score of 6.000. This model was also recommended by stepwise regression and backwards elimination, with the lowest AIC score of -6334.9. However, since the 5-predictor model including farm_acres_2 had similar BIC, AIC, and \(C_p\) scores, we will manually compare the model strength and significance using the tools we have learned in STAT-230.

fmA <- lm(farm_income_2 ~ pop_dens_2 + grazing_rotation_2 + fertilizer_use_2 + bee_colonies_2, data = df4)
mplot(fmA, which = 1)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

mplot(fmA, which = 2)

gf_dhistogram(~ residuals(fmA))

fmB <- lm(farm_income_2 ~ farm_acres_2 + pop_dens_2 + grazing_rotation_2 + fertilizer_use_2 + bee_colonies_2, data = df4)
mplot(fmB, which = 1)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

mplot(fmB, which = 2)

gf_dhistogram(~ residuals(fmB))

The residuals vs fitted plot, QQ plot, and histogram of the residuals of both models are practically identical and will not serve as a point of difference. The Linearity condition is mostly met as there is mostly symmetry over the line residual=0 on the residuals vs fitted values plot, and there does not seem to be major bending or curving of points. The Equal Variance condition is questionable as there seems to be funneling in of the spread of points on the residual vs fitted value plot as you move to higher fitted values. The Normality condition is also questionable as, though the QQ-plot is mostly a straight line with mostly no bending, there does seem to be a very large and bent tail at the high end. Furthermore, the histogram of the residuals, while it is unimodal and centered close to 0 (a little below 0 actually), there does seem to be a significant right skew. We will assume independence and randomness and proceed. Finally, there appear to be several outliers on both models.

Thankfully, for both models, none of the VIF values are above 5 which would strongly indicate multicollinearity. However, the inclusion of farm_acres_2 in fmB raises all of the VIF values by a combined 0.654. It raises the VIF value of pop_dens_2 by 0.0628, grazing_rotation_2 by 0.2001, fertilizer_use_2 by 0.2936, and bee_colonies_2 by 0.0885. The VIF of the extra predictor of fmB, farm_acres_2, is also the highest at 1.6201. This indicates that the inclusion of farm_acres_2 definitely introduced some more multicollinearity. The correlation matrix, specifically that of the farm_acres_2 pairs, isn’t too concerning with not extremely high correlation coefficients, except maybe the farm_acres_2 and fertilizer_use_2 pair which has the third highest correlation coefficient at 0.44297 indicating a moderate, linear relationship.

>Since the normality condition was not met for either model, we will test the significance of farm_acres_2 using bootstrapping. The resulting 95% confidence interval for the coefficient of farm_acres_2 is (-6.2357e-05, 5.5122e-05). Since this interval includes 0,we are not 95% confident that the farm_acres_2 is not 0, and conclude that this predictor is not significant.

Considering the t-tests for predictor coefficients, the |t-values| for fmA are all higher than those of fmB. The |t-value| of pop_dens_2 is 0.22 higher, for grazing_rotation_2 is 1.44 higher, for fertilizer_use_2 is 5.51 higher, for bee_colonies_2 is 0.13 higher. The resulting p-values all seem to be similar, except that of bee_colonies_2 which is lower for fmA indicating that bee_colonies_2 is a more significant predictor of farm_income_2 when farm_acres_2 is not included. Furthermore, the |t-value| for t-test for farm_acres_2 coefficient is quite low at 0.13, yielding a p-value that is much, much larger than any reasonable \(alpha\) indicating that we fail to reject the null hypothesis (\(H_0: \beta_{farm,acres,2} = 0\))and do not have enough evidence to conclude the alternate hypothesis (\(H_A: \beta_{farm,acres,2} \neq 0\)) that farm_acres_2 is a significant predictor of farm_income_2. Furthermore, while the residual standard error seems to be about the same, the adjusted \(R^2\) of fmB with farm_acres_2 as a predictor is very slightly lower. Furthermore, the f-statistic in the f-test is lower in the model that includes farm_acres_2 by 141 indicating less significance of the model.

##FINAL CONCLUSION:

Considering the fact that fmB had a higher BIC, higher AIC, higher Cp, had 11 more high leverage points and 16 more problematic leverage points, includes farm_acres_2 as a predictor which increased all of the VIFs of the other predictors and had the highest VIF of both models belonging to farm_acres_2 itself, demonstrated a weak relationship between the response variable farm_income_2 and the additional predictor farm_acres_2 with a low correlation coefficient and a horizontal band of points on the AV plot, yielded insignifiance of the predictor farm_acres_2 in the nested f-test, has an insignificant coefficient in bootstrap testing, increases the |t-values| of all of the other predictors besides farm_acres_2 with farm_acres_2 having the highest t-value and least significance as a predictor, has a slightly lower adjusted \(R^2\), has a lower f-statistic which would yield less significance of the model, and is more complex, I agree with the best subsets automated variable selection model and stepwise regression model to fit fmA, the 4-predictor model instead of fmB, the 5-predictor model including farm_acres_2. Qualitatively, this suprises me as I would expect the size of a farm, farm_acres_2, to be a significant predictor of farm income, farm_income_2.

Overall, our final model fmA, indicates that 50% of the variability in farm_income_2 can be explained by the multiple linear relationship between farm_income_2 and pop_dens, grazing_rotation_2, fertilizer_use_2, and bee_colonies_2.

This model indicates that average farm income in a county increases with increasing population density, use of grazing rotations, fertilizer use, and prevalence of bee colonies. Specifically, average farm income increases by $0.29 for every 1 person/acre density increase; farm income increases by $0.32 for every 1 acre increase in grazing rotations; farm income increases by $1.00 for every 1 unit increase in fertilizer application; and farm income increases by $0.36 for every 1 acre increase in bee colony coverage.
